{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}
A '''log line''' or '''logline''' is a brief (usually one-sentence) summary of a [[television program]], [[film]], or book that states the central conflict of the story, often providing both a synopsis of the story's [[Plot (narrative)|plot]], and an emotional "[[hook (rhetoric)|hook]]" to stimulate interest.  A one-sentence program summary in ''[[TV Guide]]'' is a log line.<ref>{{harvtxt|Brewer|2014|p=29}}</ref>

==Elements==

Narrative elements often referenced in a logline include the [[setting (narrative)|setting]], [[protagonist]], [[antagonist]], [[inciting incident]], [[Conflict (narrative)| conflict]] and [[goal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graemeshimmin.com/writing-a-logline-for-a-novel/|title=Writing a Logline|publisher=Graeme Shimmin|accessdate=2017-09-13}}</ref>

==Examples==
{{quote|Charlie Brown is finally invited to a Halloween party; Snoopy engages the Red Baron in a dogfight; and Linus waits patiently in the pumpkin patch                                              for the Great Pumpkin.|Logline for ''[[It's the Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://titantv.com/|title=Logline|work=[[It's the Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown]]|publisher=TitanTV|accessdate=2005-10-25}}</ref>}}

{{quote|A talented but irresponsible teenager schemes to steal his college tuition money when his wealthy father refuses to pay for him to study acting at Juilliard.|Logline for ''[[How I Paid for College:  A Novel of Sex, Theft, Friendship, and Musical Theater]]''<ref>{{harvtxt|Brewer|2014|p=29}}</ref>}}

